course: main course
time required: 45 minutes
---

Preheat your #oven to 220°C. Fill and boil your #kettle. Pour a good glug of
@oil{} onto a #baking tray{} (to completely cover the bottom) and pop in your
oven. Pour the boiling @water{for the potatoes} into a #large saucepan{} on
high heat with @salt{0.5%tsp}. Peel the @potatoes{450}, chop them into 3cm
chunks and add them to the boiling water. Cook for ~{5-6%minutes} - until the
edges have softened when you poke them with a knife.

Once the potatoes are ready, drain them in a #colander{} then pop back into the
pan then sprinkle on the @plain flour{8%g}. Give your pan a shake to fluff
them up. Take your hot baking tray out of your oven, carefully transfer your
potatoes onto it and turn in the oil, before spreading them out in a single
layer. Season with @salt{}, then roast on the top shelf of your oven until
golden, ~{30-35%minutes}, turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, open the pack with the @lamb shank{670%g} and transfer the contents
to another large saucepan. TIP: Make sure you scrape out all the juice and
jelly from the packet - it's your sauce! Pop the pan onto a medium heat and
cover with a #lid or #foil{}. Leave to bubble away for ~{15%minutes}.

Pick the @rosemary{1/2%sprig} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop
(discard the stalks). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated)
(or use a #garlic press{}). Chop the @tri-coloured Chantenay carrots{150}
lengthways. Sprinkle over the rosemary along with the @honey{15%g} and a
drizzle of @oil{}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.
~{15-20%minutes} before the roasties are ready, pop your Chantenay carrots on
the bottom shelf of your oven until golden and tender.

Once the lamb has been bubbling away for 15 mins, remove the lid or foil, pour
in the @water{200%ml} and stir in the @red wine jus paste{1%tsp} to dissolve.
Bring back to the boil and use a #dessert spoon{} to baste the lamb shanks with
the sauce. Simmer the sauce and repeat basting every ~{2%minutes} or so for
~{10-15%minutes}. The sauce will get stickier as it reduces and make the lamb
shanks sticky and shiny! Increase the heat if the sauce doesn't thicken.

~{6-7%minutes} before the roasties and carrots are ready, heat a
#medium frying pan{} on a medium-high heat. When hot, add the
@cavolo nero{100%g} and a splash of @water{}. Season with @salt{} and
@black pepper{} and stir-fry until wilted and tender, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add the
garlic and cook for a further ~{1%minute}. Share the cavolo nero on your
#plates{} and place the lamb shanks alongside. Share your carrots and potatoes
between your plates and pour over the gravy. Enjoy!